+# CVE-2025-23061 — False Positive for mongoose 5.13.23
+
+## Summary
+
+CVE-2025-23061 ("Mongoose search injection vulnerability") is flagged against
+this package by version-range-based scanners (Snyk, Dependabot, `npm audit`,
+etc.), but it does not apply to mongoose 5.13.23. The vulnerable code path
+described in the advisory does not exist in the 5.x release line.
+
+## Advisory details
+
+- **CVE:** CVE-2025-23061
+- **GHSA:** [GHSA-vg7j-7cwx-8wgw](https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-vg7j-7cwx-8wgw)
+- **Reported vulnerable ranges:** `>= 8.0.0-rc0, < 8.9.5`; `>= 7.0.0-rc0, < 7.8.4`; `< 6.13.6`
+- **Fixed by upstream commits:**
+  - [`b804e34e4d4cc670d7247fbd558c47412b4e5e01`](https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/commit/b804e34e4d4cc670d7247fbd558c47412b4e5e01) (7.x/8.x line)
+  - [`3b0c5c08b8c400f48d3823bc5b36efe2d12cb5cd`](https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/commit/3b0c5c08b8c400f48d3823bc5b36efe2d12cb5cd) (6.x line)
+- **Root cause per advisory:** an incomplete fix for CVE-2024-53900 — the
+  `sanitizeFilter()` helper only blocked `$where` when it appeared as a direct
+  key, so an attacker could still smuggle `$where`, `$expr`, `$jsonSchema`, or
+  `$text` past it (e.g. nested under `$nor`/`$not`, or via `trusted()` not
+  covering function values).
+
+## Why this doesn't apply to 5.13.23
+
+The exploit requires the `sanitizeFilter()` / `trusted()` mechanism to exist,
+because the vulnerability *is* a bypass of that mechanism. Mongoose 5.x never
+shipped that feature at all:
+
+- `lib/helpers/query/sanitizeFilter.js` — does not exist in this package
+- `lib/helpers/query/trusted.js` — does not exist in this package
+- `mongoose.trusted()` API — does not exist in this package
+- The `sanitizeFilter` schema/connection option — does not exist in this package
+
+Verified by:
+
+```
+grep -rn "sanitizeFilter\|trustedSymbol\|trusted(" lib/
+# => no matches (only unrelated `sanitizeProjection` references)
+```
+
+and by checking the `5.13.0` tag on the upstream repository, which also only
+contains `sanitizeProjection.js` under `lib/helpers/query/` — confirming the
+feature was never present anywhere in the 5.13.x line, not just removed later.
+
+`sanitizeFilter`/`trusted()` were introduced upstream in the 6.x release line.
+Applying either of the two "fix" commits above to this codebase would mean
+introducing a brand-new feature that 5.x users never had, not patching an
+existing vulnerable path.
+
+## Why the scanner still flags it
+
+GHSA/OSV vulnerable-range data for this advisory is expressed as `< 6.13.6`
+with no lower bound. That phrasing means "no fix had landed before this
+version," not "every version below 6.13.6 contains the vulnerable code."
+Range-only matching against `< 6.13.6` therefore produces a false positive for
+any 5.x (or earlier) release that predates the feature's introduction.
+
+## Disposition
+
+**Not affected / false positive.** No code change is required or applicable
+in this package for CVE-2025-23061. If reported by a scanning tool, mark it as
+"not affected" with this document as justification.
+
+## Related, unrelated fix
+
+Note that a separate, legitimate `$where`-in-`populate()` issue
+(CVE-2026-42334) *does* apply to this branch and was backported to
+`lib/helpers/populate/getModelsMapForPopulate.js` in 5.13.23. That fix is
+unrelated to `sanitizeFilter` and should not be confused with this CVE.
